{
  "doc_id": "2466",
  "text": "Second, thermally oxidized lipids decrease the concentration of tocopherols [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Lastly, thermally oxidized lipids have decreased α-tocopherol digestibility [CITATION_3] , resulting in animals absorbing less vitamin E. Unlike vitamin E, there were no oxidation and antioxidant differences in serum and liver Se concentrations. Hanson et al. reported no effect of increasing dietary levels of oxidized maize oil on liver Se concentration, but there was a trend for reduced Se concentration in serum [CITATION_4] . Similar to our results, Tabatabaei et al. found no differences in serum and liver concentration of Se in rats fed either fresh or oxidized sunflower oil [CITATION_5] . Therefore, serum vitamin E concentration appears to be a more sensitive and appropriate marker than Se for evaluating oxidative status of pigs fed oxidized maize oil.",
